##During the quarantine, the weight of the word "time" was felt for the first time

Tmagazinechina

Function description, record the changing global cultural landscape

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
This is the sixth in a series of reports, the diary of Finance Worker Huo Chao. From January 30 to February 7, Huo Chao was quarantined because he had been on the same flight as a patient with newly diagnosed pneumonia. During the eight days, he experienced "a rare life experience" (from Huo Chao's personal account) in an isolation ward outside Wuxi. We have invited him to tell our story for two reasons: First, the ability of an ordinary citizen with empathy and discipline to make a quick, socially moral judgment about the risks he faces; and second, in the information cascade triggered by the epidemic, he carefully screened for the benefit of their own psychological catharsis part, and on this basis, made a thinking. Thinking, no matter when, is a meaningful thing, especially in this was Huo Chao called "information cocoon" of the era.

On January 22,2020, I finally finished my busy year and took an early vacation from Beijing to catch a flight to Cambodia's Sihanouk Port to reunite with my working mother on New Year's Eve, with a stopover in Wuhan. While I was waiting for the plane to take off at 2 am on the 23rd, I saw on my mobile phone that the Wuhan Government had announced the closure of the city at 10 am this morning: "The city bus, subway, ferry and long-distance passenger services have been suspended; No special reason, people do not leave Wuhan, the airport, railway station from the Han Channel temporarily closed. At about the same time, the flight was delayed by one hour. My heart skipped a beat and I had a bad feeling.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Like most people in this epidemic, I have a process of going from unconscious to COVID-19. Because I studied at Wuhan University for four years, and then worked in Wuhan for four years after graduation, it can be said that the best years of my youth were in Wuhan, so it is not clear when I started, Wuhan as a second home. In early January of this year, I came across the news that there might be a SARS like virus in Wuhan, but I didn't care. It was just one of those daily flood of information that I never thought would affect my life. Until January 17, some students who were still studying in Japan thought I was still working in Wuhan, especially asking me on wechat about the situation in Wuhan. Since then, i began to consciously search for news related to the Wuhan epidemic in various media both at home and abroad. I was surprised by the difference between the two reports, so much so that for the first time I was skeptical of the "exaggerated" reports of the "free speech" foreign media.

But on the flight through Wuhan, I wore my N95 mask with care, and followed the doctor's orders from Dr. Syzygium aromaticum to wash my hands and disinfect them if necessary. Finally, my flight took off an hour later, probably the last international flight from Tianhe Airport.

In a foreign country, I still brush up on the relevant information of Wuhan from time to time. On January 27, the Cambodian Ministry of Health officially announced the country's first confirmed case, and confirmed that the patient was on a flight from Wuhan to the port of Sihanouk. As rumors swirled around the world, Chinese were snapping up the most common surgical masks at the market in Sihanoukville that day, soaring from $1 to $10 a bag. The next day, with all sorts of true and false information, the local "Chinese Chamber of Commerce" contacted me directly and told me to go to the better local hospitals in Sihanoukville for registration as soon as possible, seeing the local medical conditions, the "better hospitals" here may not be as good as the community hospitals in the first-tier cities in China, and there is also a lack of nucleic acid testing reagents, it performs only the most basic checks, as if nothing had happened.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After that, as someone who was highly suspicious of contact with a confirmed infected patient, I did my best to protect myself, wore a mask every day, and spent the rest of the day in a hotel room. I think it's not just for me, but for everyone I meet. However, whether to stay on the ground and observe the changes of the epidemic, or return to the motherland as scheduled, and choose to trust the medical conditions and the level of governance in the motherland, this is a choice put in front of many local Chinese, and I chose the latter, from Sihanouk port via Wuxi back to Beijing.

I had just landed in Wuxi on January 30. I turned on my mobile phone to let my parents know I was safe. People started to move. Everyone got up and started packing from the luggage rack. However, the announcement on the plane suddenly rang, "Mr. Huo Chao, the passenger on this flight, "As your previous flight was COVID-19 with a confirmed case, please proceed to the boarding gate and remain in your seats... " 

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The day before I returned to China, I read a story about a dispute between a Shanghai man and a Wuhan Man on a return flight, so I felt a chill in my heart as I stood in the cabin. Fortunately, although some people were whispering, the vast majority of passengers saw me go forward, get Out of my way. Customs and medical staff in Wuxi immediately guided me to the boarding gate and patiently monitored my temperature and asked me about my health.

They explained that according to the big data provided by the Public Security Bureau, it had been made clear that the flight I had been on had been diagnosed with a patient, and that in accordance with the special circumstances of the current epidemic and relevant regulations, I would be detained in Wuxi and placed in isolation on the spot. At the same time, the customs officers also asked me to specify their whereabouts from a certain date.

Whether you like it or not, the information age brings with it a loss of privacy -- whether it's a digital one or a government one, but this loss of privacy is already inevitable. So I took the initiative to account for all my movements, because I understood that all my movements in the country also generated data, and the only possible question was whether all the information had been put together into a system, and Right now, the best way to protect yourself and the people you meet is to come clean and avoid slip ups.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The News of my decision to be quarantined did not alarm me, but rather reassured me that it was better to have such a clear answer than to have been left to wonder. And now that I'm in the country, medical hardware and software can make me feel a lot better than I did in Cambodia, and I still remember my family telling me to make sure I put a $5 tip in my passport when I cross the border from Sihanouk, so the Cambodian customs officers don't mess with your luggage.

The rest of it, for me, was a lot of firsts. Under the guidance of Customs officers, the first time through the open channel of diplomatic courtesy; under the guidance of medical staff, the first time on the ambulance in the hospital; under the guidance of the isolation staff, the relevant procedures for the quarantine check-in... .

If there is any doubt or concern in this process, it is certainly there. However, I have been immersed in the media's all-round, multi-angle and three-dimensional propaganda for so many days, and I also know that this epidemic will not happen overnight, and don't take it for granted. As an ordinary law-abiding citizens, as much as possible a little bit of cooperation, to do their part, I believe that as long as through the Cold Yin tunnel, you can see the light.

The living conditions of the isolated accommodation are not so different from what I expected: isolated accommodation transformed from single-occupancy housing in an industrial area in a remote part of the city. Can guarantee the basic life, but also only the basic life, certainly far from the comfortable comfortable comfortable home. But with the epidemic raging, resources are scarce, I understand.

If I hadn't been there, I would have thought that the isolation building would have been similar to the Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn's cancer tower, but I have observed that the wechat group, my fellow Internet users were in a much happier state than I had expected and were not "over-involved" in the panic. In addition to complaining and consulting about Life Problems, of course, the most common problem is eating... then there is communication, encouragement, encouragement, and support for the medical staff online cheer. Looking back, I only heard the sound of an ambulance once during the eight days I was in quarantine. As you can imagine, I'm in a quarantine zone that's generally healthy, both physically and mentally.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Also for my own mental health, I began to write a long-winded "isolation diary" on the Internet, adding a way to pass time. Although I understand that these words are written on the water, the moment passed, but now that there is this rare opportunity to be careful, it is better to take the opportunity to write more, more thinking, more to forget the memorial.

On the fifth day of my stay in quarantine, the CDC nucleic acid doctor began giving me my first nucleic acid test. After talking to my doctor, I finally understood two official explanations of my situation: First, it was not to be quarantined for 14 days from the date of entry (January 30) , but from the date of contact (January 23) ; and second, i'm a "close contact" in intensive isolation, and I'm the lightest of the four.

* PATIENT: Intensive Care
* PATIENT-LIKE: centralized isolation
* Febrile patients: Observation under concentrated isolation
* CONTACTEE: under close observation

Confirmed patients: Intensive Care

Suspected patient: Concentrated Isolation

Febrile patients: Isolated and observed

Close contacts: under close observation in isolation

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Every day in the isolation room, I would regularly watch the news related to the epidemic, often laughing, watching and crying; crying, watching and laughing... so I would give myself a time limit, limit Yourself to one hour a day to browse through information about the outbreak. However, as I log on to various video sites each day, it's frightening to think that the ever more accurate big data algorithm, dubbed -- as a push -- is so sweet and reasonable that it won't make you choke on it, it just keeps going, so much so that even though it seems like there's Wi-Fi, there's the Internet, and there's a connection to the outside world, I'm still stuck in a cocoon of information, being fed information on the other end of the network.

If we face the "new coronavirus" , we can also put on a mask and hide in a room. In the face of the Internet, the instant gratification that one click brings is not only hard to refuse, but it also extends endlessly, from online to offline, from goods to services..

On the 14th day of my second nucleic acid test, the phrase I saw most frequently in my circles was "a speck of dust from the age, a mountain on a person's head, " by Wuhan Writer Fang Fang. The only thing we have to do is take it all on.".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In 1998, when state owned enterprises were laid off and my parents'decades of service were replaced with wool, I had little memory of the 6 year old; in 2003, SARS was raging in the capital, now just two hours from my home on the high speed rail, at the age of 11, I was happy with the holiday that came with the suspension; in 2008, the moment of the Wenchuan County earthquake, I was about to take my senior high school entrance exam and felt the earth shake, but the teacher calmly continued to teach... but now, for every Chinese suffering from an epidemic of varying severity, I would like to quote from the beginning of this series of reports in the Chinese edition of t: "though at a safe distance from the new coronavirus, but it is also inescapably caught up in the moment, experiencing its horrors with every fiber of its being.".

For perhaps the first time, I actually felt the weight of the word "time. ".

The day before yesterday, after I had been under observation for eight days, I packed my bags and asked the medical staff if I could get a taxi now. Her answer was that, since she had been working here recently, it was not clear what was going on outside. When I was about to leave the quarantine zone, I took a picture of the medical lady in a heavy protective suit outside the first floor entrance. She quickly sprayed disinfectant on my hands and told me to leave the quarantine zone earlier. It was dangerous here, it's safer outside. She immediately went back to work. I suddenly found that behind my isolation, there are actually so many people silently bless you, silently watch over you, and they still continue, still insist.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In 1919, Lu Xun published an essay in the new youth, later included in the essay collection hot wind. He wrote: "May the youth of China be free from the Cold Air, but go upward, without listening to the stream of the self-abnegation. ". Who can do things, who can speak. A minute of heat, a minute of light, like fireflies, but also in the dark to send a little light, do not have to wait for the torch. If there is no torch after that, I am the only light. "

Make It hot, make it light, make it dark. I believe that hope is not far away.
